      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented release notes and regression test suite covering blood pump geometries.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 was used under a validated software quality management plan. Version control records, regression test logs, and release notes were reviewed and found compliant with the required level for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmarked against at least one analytical or manufactured solution for laminar and turbulent internal flow.",
      "rationale": "The solver was verified against the Hagen-Poiseuille analytical solution for laminar pipe flow and a manufactured solution for the k-omega SST turbulence model. Results were within 0.3% of analytical values, satisfying the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal grid convergence study using Richardson extrapolation across at least three systematically refined meshes, with GCI reported for all quantities of interest.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was conducted using two mesh densities (4.2 M and 8.7 M elements) for the nominal pump geometry. The hemolysis index differed by 6.8% between the two meshes, and the finer mesh was selected for all production runs based on this comparison. The team notes that the laboratory has conducted over a dozen prior CFD hemolysis studies using analogous mesh refinement protocols, and expert judgment from three senior engineers with a combined 40 years of turbomachinery CFD experience supports the conclusion that the 8.7 M element mesh is adequate for capturing the dominant shear stress gradients responsible for hemolysis in this pump class. Additionally, sensitivity analyses of the scalar stress model parameters showed that hemolysis predictions varied by less than 9% across the plausible parameter range, which the team interpreted as indirect evidence that spatial discretization error is not a dominant uncertainty source. On this basis, the credibility assessment team concluded that the discretization error factor is sufficiently controlled for the purposes of this COU, and the overall package was advanced to the acceptance decision. A third mesh level was planned but not completed due to computational resource constraints within the project timeline; the team considers the two-mesh comparison, combined with prior experience and the parameter sensitivity data, to constitute adequate evidence for the intended regulatory submission context."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, temperature, flow rates) documented and shown to match CFD boundary conditions within specified tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Bench test conditions were documented in the laboratory protocol. Fluid temperature was maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C, viscosity measured at 0.0035 ± 0.0002 Pa·s, and flow rates controlled within ±2% of target. CFD boundary conditions were set to match the mean measured values. Correspondence between test and simulation conditions was verified by the test engineer and independently reviewed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted hemolysis index against experimental measurements at all 5 operating points, with agreement within ±15%.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against experimental measurements at all 5 flow-speed operating points. Agreement ranged from 3.1% to 13.7% across the operating envelope, with a mean absolute error of 8.4%. All comparisons fell within the ±15% acceptance band. Systematic over-prediction at high-speed conditions was noted and attributed to turbulence model limitations, which are addressed in the model form factor assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QOIs used in validation (NIH, relative hemolysis index RH) are directly mapped to the clinical decision criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The primary QOI, normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), is directly used to compute the relative hemolysis index RH referenced in the regulatory acceptance criterion. The mapping from CFD shear stress fields through the scalar stress model to NIH and then to RH is fully documented in the simulation plan. No surrogate quantities are used."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/cou1-relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under CPB-representative operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were performed using the FDA benchmark centrifugal blood pump geometry under operating conditions representative of CPB use (flow rates 2–6 L/min, speeds 2500–3500 RPM). The validation domain overlaps with the COU operating envelope, supporting direct applicability of the validation evidence to the intended regulatory use."
    },
